Kayode Oyero The President, Major General Muhammadu Buhari (retd.), has said carrying on with Nigeria’s democracy for 21 years has been “a collective struggle”. The retired major general stated this during his 2020 Democracy Day Speech on Friday, while celebrating the nation’s founding fathers and everyone who ensured that Nigeria’s democracy has been sustained. He said, “It is a day to honour our founding fathers who toiled to establish our republic and every Nigerian who has worked tirelessly to sustain it. “Sustaining our democracy thus far has been a collective struggle, and I congratulate all Nigerians and particularly leaders of our democratic institutions on their resilience and determination to ensure that Nigeria remains a shining example of democracy.” Buhari appreciated the commitment and sacrifice of all health workers and other essential staff on the frontlines in the battle against the coronavirus pandemic. READ ALSO: External reserves grew from $33.42bn to $36bn in May – Buhari “We are celebrating this year’s Democracy Day despite the COVID-19 pandemic which afflicts our nation and the whole world. “It is indeed a very difficult time for everyone especially those who have lost loved ones to the virus and those whose sources of livelihood have been severely constrained by the stringent measures we introduced at every level of government to contain the virus and save lives. “The dedication of our health and other essential services staff towards containing this virus is a testament of our courage and resilience as a people and as a great nation, and I use this opportunity to say thank you to all of you for your service to the nation,” the President said.